/>Merges are commits too. And merges need commit messages too. They need<br />an explanation of what they do - and why - the same way a normal<br />commit does.<br /><br />You wouldn't make a one-liner "Do this" message for a regular commit<br />that has big implications. Why do you think it's ok for a merge<br />commit?<br /><br />When you merge something, the individual commits that get pulled in<br />hopefully have their own explanations for each individual change -<br />otherwise you definitely shouldn't merge them. So the merge doesn't<br />need to replicate all of that.<br /><br />But the merge itself still needs a "why am I merging these commits" explanation.<br /><br />We pride ourselves on good commit messages. But that merge commit<br />message is pure and utter garbage.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
